Goldfields Open|2012]]\n| [[Australian Goldfields Open]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Barry Hawkins]]\n| align=\"center\"| 3\u20139\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Runner-up\n| 9.\n| [[2018 Paul Hunter Classic|2018]]\n| [[Paul Hunter Classic]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Kyren Wilson]]\n| align=\"center\"| 2\u20134\n|}\n\n===Non-ranking finals: 6 (4 titles, 2 runner-ups)===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"80\"|'''Outcome'''\n!width=\"20\"|'''No.'''\n!width=\"50\"|'''Year'''\n!width=\"250\"|'''Championship'''\n!width=\"200\"|'''Opponent in the final'''\n!width=\"50\"|'''Score'''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 1.\n| [[1995 Irish Masters|1995]]\n| [[Irish Masters]]\n| {{Flagicon|SCO}} {{sortname|Stephen|Hendry}}\n| align=\"center\"| 9\u20138\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 2.\n| [[1995 Pontins Professional|1995]]\n| [[Pontins Professional]]\n| {{Flagicon|IRL}} {{sortname|Ken|Doherty}}\n| align=\"center\"| 9\u20138\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Runner-up\n| 1.\n| [[1995 Scottish Masters|1995]]\n| [[Scottish Masters]]\n| {{Flagicon|SCO}} {{sortname|Stephen|Hendry}}\n| align=\"center\"| 5\u20139\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 3.\n| [[1995 Malta Grand Prix|1995]]\n| [[Malta Grand Prix]]\n| {{Flagicon|SCO}} {{sortname|John|Higgins|dab=snooker player}}\n| align=\"center\"| 7\u20134\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 4.\n| [[1996 Scottish Masters|1996]]\n| [[Scottish Masters]]\n| {{Flagicon|SCO}} {{sortname|Alan|McManus}}\n| align=\"center\"| 9\u20136\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Runner-up\n| 2.\n| [[2002 Irish Masters|2002]]\n| [[Irish Masters]]\n| {{Flagicon|SCO}} {{sortname|John|Higgins|dab=snooker player}}\n| align=\"center\"| 3\u201310\n|}\n\n===Pro-am finals: 5 (4 titles, 1 runner-up)===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"80\"|'''Outcome'''\n!width=\"20\"|'''No.'''\n!width=\"50\"|'''Year'''\n!width=\"250\"|'''Championship'''\n!width=\"200\"|'''Opponent in the final'''\n!width=\"50\"|'''Score'''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 1.\n| 1989\n| [[Pontins Open#Pontins Spring Open|Pontins Spring Open]]\n| {{Flagicon|IRL}} {{sortname|Ken|Doherty}}\n| align=\"center\"| 7\u20134<ref name=\"web.archive.org\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/pontins.html|title=pontins|date=28 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228200841/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/pontins.html|archive-date=28 February 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 2.\n| 1990\n| Dutch Open\n| {{Flagicon|ENG}} {{sortname|Tony|Knowles|dab=snooker player}}\n| align=\"center\"| 6\u20134\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Runner-up\n| 1.\n| 1995\n| [[Pontins Open#Pontins Spring Open|Pontins Spring Open]]\n| {{Flagicon|WAL}} {{sortname|Mark|Williams|dab=snooker player}}\n| align=\"center\"| 4\u20137<ref name=\"web.archive.org\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 3.\n| 2015\n| [[Vienna Snooker Open]]\n| {{Flagicon|ENG}} {{sortname|Mark|King|dab=snooker player}}\n| align=\"center\"| 5\u20133\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 4.\n| 2016\n| [[Vienna Snooker Open]] <small>(2)</small>\n| {{Flagicon|ENG}} {{sortname|Mark|Davis|dab=snooker player}}\n| align=\"center\"| 5\u20131\n|}\n\n===Amateur finals: 1 (1 title)===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!width=\"80\"|'''Outcome'''\n!width=\"20\"|'''No.'''\n!width=\"50\"|'''Year'''\n!width=\"250\"|'''Championship'''\n!width=\"200\"|'''Opponent in the final'''\n!width=\"50\"|'''Score'''\n|- \n| style=\"background:#98FB98\"|Winner\n| 1.\n| 1990\n| [[IBSF World Under-21 Snooker Championship|IBSF World Under-21 Championship]]\n| {{Flagicon|ENG}} Oliver King\n| align=\"center\"| 11\u20139\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Peter Ebdon}}\n*[http://www.worldsnooker.com/players/peter-ebdon/ Peter Ebdon] at ''worldsnooker.com''\n* \n* [http://prosnookerblog.com/players/d-f/peter-ebdon/ Player Profile on Pro Snooker]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/2924305.stm Player Profile on BBC Sport]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090220123313/http://uk.yahoo.eurosport.com/snooker/person_prs32311.shtml Profile on Yahoo! Sport]\n* [http://www.worldsnooker.com/players/peter-ebdon/ Peter Ebdon]\n{{World snooker champions}}\n{{Snooker player of the year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ebdon, Peter}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Kettering]]\n[[Category:Snooker players from London]]\n[[Category:UK champions (snooker)]]\n[[Category:Winners of the professional snooker world championship]]\n[[Category:World Snooker Hall of Fame inductees]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Peter Ebden}}\n{{short description|English professional snooker player, 2002 world champion, 2006 UK champion}}\n{{shortlead|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n|name         = Peter Ebdon\n|image        = Peter Ebdon PHC 2018-5.jpg\n|caption      = Paul Hunter Classic 2018 \n|birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1970|8|27}}\n|birth_place   = [[Islington]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| Sport country = {{ENG}}\n| Nickname     = {{unbulleted list |The Force |Psycho |The World's Most Dangerous Man |The Ebdonator |Mr Intensity |The Plant-Based Potter}}\n| Professional = 1991\u2013\n| High ranking = 3 {{small|([[Snooker world rankings 1996/1997|1996/97]] &amp; [[Snooker world rankings 2002/2003|2002/03]])}} \n| Prize money  = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]3,583,752\n| High break   = '''[[Maximum break|147]]''' {{small|(2 times)}} \n| Century break = 377\n| Ranking wins = 9\n| Other wins   = 4\n| World champ  = [[2002 World Snooker Championship|2002]]\n}}\n'''Peter David Ebdon''' (born 27 August 1970)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/2287012|title=Peter Ebdon|website=www.thegazette.co.uk|access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref> is an English professional [[snooker]] player. He was [[World Snooker Championship|World Champion]] in [[2002 World Snooker Championship|2002]], beating [[Stephen Hendry]] 18\u201317 in the final, and won the [[UK Championship]] in [[2006 UK Championship (snooker)|2006]] and seven other ranking events between 1993 and 2012. He was also a losing finalist in the World Championship in 1996 and 2006. Ebdon turned professional in 1991 and beat six-time world champion [[Steve Davis]] 10\u20134 in the first round of the 1992 World Championship.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early years===\nEbdon turned professional in 1991. Sporting a ponytail, he made an impact by beating [[Steve Davis]] 10\u20134 in the first round of the [[1992 World Snooker Championship|1992 World Championship]]; he went on to reach the quarter-finals of the event, losing 7\u201313 to a resurgent [[Terry Griffiths]]. However, it was a run which earned him the WPBSA Young Player of the Year award as a result. His first ranking title was the 1993 [[World Open (snooker)|Grand Prix]].<ref name=\"autogenerated\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/world_champs_2002/1971162.stm|title=Ebdon's road to greatness|date=7 May 2002|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> He climbed the rankings rapidly to reach a career-highest position of number three in 1996; he again reached world number three status at the close of the 2002 season.\n\n===2002\u20132010===\nEbdon's greatest achievement, thus far, was his 18\u201317 defeat of [[Stephen Hendry]] in the [[2002 World Snooker Championship|2002 World Championship]] final,<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4156/is_20020922/ai_n12578469 The Sunday Herald: Cue Peter; Stewart Fisher talks to the champion who believes there is]</ref> having started the tournament at odds of 33\u20131.<ref name=\"autogenerated\" /> He had previously reached the final of the tournament in [[1996 World Snooker Championship|1996]], which he lost 12\u201318 to Hendry, and was also runner-up at the [[2006 World Snooker Championship|2006 event]] to [[Graeme Dott]] in which, at 7\u201315 down coming into the final session, Ebdon won six successive frames before Dott prevailed 18\u201314. In the semi-final before the final he led [[Marco Fu]] 15\u20139 before being pegged back to 16\u201316 before Ebdon took the decider, at the end of which he shed tears of relief.\n\nEbdon is a remarkably focused and determined player. Until recently, his shot times had slowed down considerably; this attracted some criticism \u2013 particularly, in his match against [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] in the [[2005 World Snooker Championship|2005 World Championship]]. Resuming at 6\u201310 down, Ebdon won the first six frames of the evening session, at one stage taking three minutes over a shot, and five minutes to compile a break of 12. Ebdon nevertheless won the match 13\u201311.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2005/apr/28/snooker.uk|title=Snooker: O'Sullivan ground down and out|first=Clive Everton at The|last=Crucible|date=28 April 2005|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> Such performances, though lacking fluency, often appear to break his opponent mentally. Ebdon stated after his victory over O'Sullivan, \"When I'm trying my hardest I seem to go slow. I don't do it intentionally\". When ''[[The Times]]'' described his slow play as 'cheating', he attempted to sue them for libel and lost.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alastair |last=Brett |title=Snookered by fair comment |date=17 April 2007 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/law/article1659968.ece |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612041058/http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/law/article1659968.ece |archivedate=12 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAmong Ebdon's other career highlights was winning the [[2006 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] in 2006, beating [[Stephen Hendry]] 10\u20136 in the final<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billiardpulse.com/2006/12/peter-ebdon-wins-uk-championship.html|title=Peter Ebdon wins UK Championship}}</ref> \u2013 in doing so, becoming only the ninth player to have won both the World and UK Championship. Ebdon's shot times were markedly quicker, and this fluency served him well in defeating the defending champion [[Ding Junhui]] and [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] en route to the final, and compiling eight century-breaks over the course of the tournament. However, he failed to reach a ranking quarter-final in 2007. His poor form continued into 2008; in the Northern Ireland Trophy he lost 0\u20135 to [[Liang Wenbo]] with a highest break of 32, a result which led to an investigation of suspicious betting patterns by the Gambling Commission. The WPBSA, however, did not launch an investigation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamblingplanet.org/Walker_Worries_Over_Ebdon_Liang|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081008233145/http://www.gamblingplanet.org/Walker_Worries_Over_Ebdon_Liang|title=Gambling Planet.org: Walker Admits Worries Over Ebdon-Liang|archivedate=8 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/sep/21/snooker|title=Snooker: Probe into 5-0 Peter Ebdon defeat|first=Clive|last=Everton|date=20 September 2008|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> In 2009, Ebdon beat [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] 10\u20138 to win the [[China Open 2009 (snooker)|China Open]]. However, in the subsequent [[2009 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], Ebdon lost 5\u201310 to [[Nigel Bond]] in the first round. A year later, after a disappointing season, Ebdon once again lost 5\u201310 in the [[2010 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], this time to Graeme Dott. This result meant Ebdon dropped out of the top 16 in the world rankings after an uninterrupted 16-year stay.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/8634466.stm | work=BBC News | title=Ebdon drops out of world's top 16 | date=22 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2010/2011===\n[[File:Ebdon.jpg|thumb|2010 Brugge Open]]\nAt the start of the [[Snooker season 2010/2011|season]] Ebdon issued a statement announcing that he would not be able to play to the best of his ability in the last round of the [[2010 Shanghai Masters#Qualifying|Shanghai Masters qualifiers]].<ref name=\"Peter Ebdon plays down his Shanghai Masters chances \">{{cite news\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/8864082.stm\n| title = Peter Ebdon plays down his Shanghai Masters chances \n| work = [[BBC Sport]]\n| publisher = [[BBC]]\n| date = 28 July 2010\n| accessdate = 4 August 2010\n| location=}}</ref>\nHe reached the second round of the tournament though by winning his qualifying match by 5\u20131 against Michael White, and then his last 32 match against [[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]] 5\u20134 before losing against Mark King 3\u20135. He enjoyed a good return of form in the World Open, where he beat Steve Davis 3\u20131, [[Fergal O'Brien]] 3\u20132, [[Liu Song]] 3\u20132, and [[Martin Gould]] 3\u20131 before losing against [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] 1\u20133. This was his first semi-final since the [[2009 China Open (snooker)|2009 China Open]] and saw him retake a place in the top 16. He also reached the quarter-finals of the [[2011 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] and the last 16 of the [[2011 German Masters|German Masters]] and [[2011 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]].<ref name=\"Ebdon Results\">{{cite web | url=http://www.snookerdatabase.co.uk/PlayerDetails.aspx?PlayerKey=18&tourns=AllRank&plStat=1#PlayerResults | title=Peter Ebdon | publisher=Snooker Database | accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref> However, he was knocked out in the first round of both the [[2010 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] and [[2011 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], but was still ranked as number 13 at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rankings after 2011 World Championship |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/64/71/0,,13165~160100,00.pdf |work=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |accessdate=30 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5yTSNTAng?url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/64/71/0,,13165~160100,00.pdf |archivedate=6 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===2011/2012===\nEbdon lost in the first round of the first two ranking events of the year, the [[2011 Australian Goldfields Open|Australian Goldfields Open]] and the [[2011 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]], to make a low key start to the season and as a result drop out of the top 16 at the first cut-off in October, meaning he now had to win a qualifying match to reach the main draw of the ranking events.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rankings after PTC6 (2011 Warsaw Classic) |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/dc/8f/0,,13165~167900,00.pdf |work=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |accessdate=30 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029190034/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/dc/8f/0%2C%2C13165~167900%2C00.pdf |archivedate=29 October 2013 }}</ref> He lost his first qualifying match in an attempt to reach the [[2011 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] as he was defeated 3\u20136 by [[Robert Milkins]]. The result meant that Ebdon would not play in the tournament since his first year as a professional in 1991.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/9358949.Ex_snooker_champion_Peter_Ebdon_to___miss_return_to_York/ | title=Ex-snooker champion Peter Ebdon to miss return to York | newspaper=[[The Press (York)|The Press]] | date=11 November 2011 | accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref> He also missed the [[Masters (snooker)|Masters]] for the first time since 1992 due to being ranked outside of the top 16, but did manage to qualify for the [[2012 German Masters|German Masters]] and the [[2012 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]], losing in the first round upon reaching the venue in both events.<ref name=\"Ebdon Results\"/>\n\nHe had a disastrous run of form in the [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012|PTC]] series, as he played in all 12 events but could only win 4 matches all season. He finished 98th in the [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012#Order of Merit|Order of Merit]] and these results contributed to Ebdon being ranked world number 28 in March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10&season=2011|title=Order of Merit|publisher=WWW Snooker|date=8 January 2012|accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rankings after 2012 PTC Finals|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/ef/a3/0,,13165~173039,00.pdf|work=worldsnooker.com|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]]|accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nEbdon put his indifferent form behind him at the [[2012 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] where he won the ninth ranking event title of his career. He whitewashed [[Liang Wenbo]] 5\u20130 to qualify and once in China beat [[Matthew Stevens]] 5\u20133 to set up a last 16 meeting with [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]]. He came back from 1\u20133 down and, despite Higgins finding a snooker he needed in the final frame, he held his nerve to take the match 5\u20134 and his reach his fourth successive China Open quarter-final.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-2122307/John-Higgins-China-Open-exit.html?ito=feeds-newsxml | title=Ebdon forces World champion Higgins into early China Open exit | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | date=29 March 2012 | accessdate=30 March 2012 | location=London}}</ref> There he beat [[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]] 5\u20133 to play local favourite [[Ding Junhui]] in the semi-finals. Ebdon again came back from 1\u20133 down, this time winning five successive frames to take the match 6\u20133 and make it to his first ranking event final since winning the same tournament three years earlier.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-2123179/Peter-Ebdon-beats-Ding-Junhui-meet-Stephen-Maguire-China-Open-final.html?ito=feeds-newsxml | title=Ebdon sees off home favourite Ding to set up China Open final against Maguire | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | date=31 March 2012 | accessdate=1 April 2012 | location=London}}</ref> In the final he played [[Stephen Maguire]] and built a 5\u20131 lead in the first session, which was cut by three frames due to slow play. However, Maguire won seven of the next ten frames to level the match at 8 frames apiece. The final three frames were error strewn and slow, but with the clock approaching 01:00&nbsp;am [[Time in China#People's Republic of China|Beijing time]], Ebdon clinched the frame he required to win the eight-hour match 10\u20139. The result saw him rise seven places in the rankings to number 21 and during the final he recorded the 300th century break of his career.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/other-sports/snooker/peter-ebdon-beat-stephen-maguire-778590 | title=Ebdon fends off Maguire magic to win thrilling China Open final | newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]] | date=1 April 2012 | accessdate=1 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://au.eurosport.com/snooker/ebdon-edges-maguire_sto3218584/story.shtml | title=Ebdon edges Maguire in epic final | publisher=[[Eurosport]] | date=1 April 2012 | accessdate=1 April 2012}}</ref> He made six century breaks during the tournament, the most of any player \u2013 four of which were in the final.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://asia.eurosport.com/snooker/china-open-century-breaks_sto2729890/story.shtml | title=China Open century breaks | publisher=[[Eurosport]] Asia | accessdate=2 April 2012| date=April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nHe continued his recent surge of form into the [[2012 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] by recording a 10\u20130 whitewash over [[Alfred Burden|Alfie Burden]] in qualifying.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/apr/16/ronnie-osullivan-peter-ebdon-world-championship | title=Ronnie O'Sullivan to play Peter Ebdon in world championship first round | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | date=16 April 2012 | accessdate=16 April 2012 | location=London}}</ref> However, his season was ended when he drew [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] in the first round and lost 4\u201310, meaning he has failed to beat ''The Rocket'' since their infamous [[2005 World Snooker Championship|2005]] quarter-final.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cuetracker.net/pages/h2h.php?ID1=8&ID2=18 | title=Head-to-Head for Peter Ebdon vs Ronnie O'Sullivan | publisher=Cue Tracker | accessdate=24 April 2012 }}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Despite his win in China, Ebdon finished the season ranked world number 20 meaning he had dropped 7 places during the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/1d/b0/0,,13165~176157,00.pdf |title=Official World Ranking List for the 2012/2013 Season |accessdate=20 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69tDLWozD?url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/1d/b0/0,,13165~176157,00.pdf |archivedate=13 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===2012/2013===\nEbdon began the [[Snooker season 2012/2013|season]] by qualifying for the [[2012 Wuxi Classic|Wuxi Classic]] and lost 4\u20135 to an in-form [[Stuart Bingham]] in the first round.<ref name=\"2012/13\">{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=42&season=2012 | title=Peter Ebdon 2012/2013 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=18 July 2012}}</ref> He then played in the [[2012 Australian Goldfields Open|Australian Goldfields Open]], beating [[Michael Holt (snooker player)|Michael Holt]], [[Ding Junhui]] and [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]] all by 5\u20134 scorelines.<ref name=\"2012/13\"/> The match against Ding caused a degree of controversy as Ebdon had taken an average of 32 seconds a shot in a nine frame encounter lasting almost 5 hours.<ref name=\"aus controversy\">{{cite web | url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/trump-slams-ebdon-win-ding-145234803.html | title=Trump slams Ebdon after win over Ding | publisher=[[Eurosport]] | accessdate=12 July 2012 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120715045713/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/trump-slams-ebdon-win-ding-145234803.html | archivedate=15 July 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> In the semi-finals he defeated [[Marco Fu]] 6\u20132, despite his opponent having over a 90% pot success, 80% long pot success and 80% in his safety game success.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2849331,00.html |title=Ebdon into Final With Win Over Fu |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=18 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718015341/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~2849331%2C00.html |archivedate=18 July 2012 }}</ref> He faced [[Barry Hawkins]] in the final and succumbed to a 3\u20139 defeat,<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/18848619 | title=Australian Open 2012: Barry Hawkins defeats Peter Ebdon | date=16 July 2012}}</ref> admitting afterwards that he had struggled in every department of his game.<ref name=\"aus final\">{{cite web|title=Hawkins on Top Down Under|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2850028,00.html|work=worldsnooker.com|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]]|date=15 July 2012|accessdate=18 July 2012}}</ref> Ebdon lost in the first round of the [[2012 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]], but continued his good start to the season at the inaugural [[2012 International Championship|International Championship]]. He received a bye through the first round as [[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]] had been suspended due to match fixing allegations,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-2216917/Stephen-Lee-suspended-snooker-betting-investigation-takes-place.html | title=Lee suspended from snooker as investigation takes place into suspicious betting patterns | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | accessdate=19 April 2013 | location=London | date=12 October 2012}}</ref> and only conceded one frame in beating [[Stephen Maguire]] and [[Ricky Walden]] to advance to the semi-finals.<ref name=\"2012/13\"/> There he was thrashed 1\u20139 by [[Judd Trump]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/20182609 | title=Judd Trump beats Peter Ebdon to become world number one | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref> \n\nDuring the rest of the season Ebdon lost in qualifying for three ranking events and in the first round of the [[2013 World Open (snooker)|World Open]] and the [[2013 China Open (snooker)|China Open]].<ref name=\"2012/13\"/> He qualified for the [[2013 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] by coming back from 6\u20138 to beat [[Kurt Maflin]] 10\u20138 and played [[Graeme Dott]] in the first round, a repeat of the [[2006 World Snooker Championship|2006]] final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3144388,00.html |title=White Denied By Milkins |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=19 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130418002037/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~3144388%2C00.html |archivedate=18 April 2013 }}</ref> His place in the main draw meant Ebdon equalled [[Steve Davis]] by featuring in 22 consecutive appearances in the tournament, second only to [[Stephen Hendry]]'s record of 27.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/22188014 | title=World Snooker Championship: O'Sullivan is hot favourite \u2013 Ebdon | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref> His match against Dott lasted seven hours, spread over three sessions as Ebdon battled back from 2\u20136 to level at 6\u20136, before losing the last four frames to succumb to a 6\u201310 defeat.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/22247115 | title=World Snooker Championship 2013: Graeme Dott beats Ebdon | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=23 April 2013}}</ref> Dott called for new rules to be brought in to combat slow play after the match.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/22268829 | title=World Snooker Championship 2013: Dott wants rule change | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=23 April 2013}}</ref> Ebdon fell 10 places in the end of season rankings to world number 30.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/49/bc/0,,13165~179273,00.pdf |title=Official World Snooker Ranking List for the 2013/2014 Season |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=28 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130611202605/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/49/bc/0%2C%2C13165~179273%2C00.pdf |archivedate=11 June 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===2013/2014===\n[[File:Peter Ebdon at Snooker German Masters (Martin Rulsch) 2014-01-29 02.jpg|thumb|2014 German Masters]]\nEbdon had a slow start to the [[Snooker season 2013/2014|2013/2014 season]] as in the opening four ranking events he lost in the first round twice and failed to qualify for the other two.<ref name=\"2013/14\">{{cite web|title=Peter Ebdon 2013/2014|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2013&player=42|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=16 April 2014}}</ref> His form improved at the [[2013 International Championship|International Championship]] with victories over [[Jack Lisowski]] and [[Mark Joyce]]. Ebdon then held his nerve against [[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]] to win 6\u20135 after having led 5\u20133 and revealed afterwards that he was trying to speed up his game. Robertson called Ebdon an all-time great and stated that he could beat his quarter-final opponent [[Ding Junhui]] if he could play the same again.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12243/8999432/international-championship-peter-ebdon-progresses-at-neil-robertsons-expense | title=International Championship: Peter Ebdon progresses at Neil Robertson's expense | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] | accessdate=16 April 2014}}</ref> Ding had won the previous two ranking events and, although the match lasted four hours, he beat Ebdon 6\u20133.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/24763477 | title=Ding Junhui beats Peter Ebdon at International Championship | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=16 April 2014}}</ref> He could not advance beyond the second round of a ranking event until the penultimate tournament, the [[2014 China Open (snooker)|China Open]].<ref name=\"2013/14\"/> Ebdon eliminated [[Jimmy Robertson (snooker player)|Jimmy Robertson]] 5\u20133 and won a deciding frame against [[Judd Trump]], saying later that he proved he could still beat the best players in the game.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12243/9245655/china-open-peter-ebdon-upsets-judd-trump-as-jimmy-white-also-progresses | title=China Open: Peter Ebdon upsets Judd Trump as Jimmy White also progresses | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] | accessdate=16 April 2014}}</ref> In the third round he was defeated 3\u20135 by [[Ali Carter]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espn.co.uk/snooker/sport/story/296857.html | title=Defending champion Robertson survives scare in China | publisher=[[ESPN (UK)]] | accessdate=16 April 2014}}</ref> Ebdon's proud 22-year playing streak in the [[2014 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] ended this season as he lost 8\u201310 against Finland's [[Robin Hull]] to miss the event for the first time since turning professional.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/27058823 | title=World Snooker Championship: Peter Ebdon fails to reach Crucible | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2014/2015===\n[[File:Peter Ebdon at Snooker German Masters (DerHexer) 2015-02-04 02.jpg|thumb|2015 German Masters]]\nThe [[Snooker season 2014/2015|2014/2015 season]] was the first time since [[Snooker season 1992/1993|1992/1993]] that Ebdon failed to play in a ranking event quarter-final, with three last 16 finishes being his deepest runs.<ref name=\"2014/15\">{{cite web|title=Peter Ebdon 2014/2015|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2014&player=42|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> He did have his best year so far in the minor-ranking [[Players Tour Championship 2014/2015|European Tour]] as a quarter-final appearance at the [[European Tour 2014/2015 \u2013 Event 1|Riga Open]] and a semi-final at the [[European Tour 2014/2015 \u2013 Event 3|Bulgarian Open]] saw him ranked 13th on the [[Players Tour Championship 2014/2015#European Tour|Order of Merit]], to make his debut at the [[Players Tour Championship 2014/2015 \u2013 Finals|Grand Final]] where he lost 1\u20134 to [[Anthony McGill (snooker player)|Anthony McGill]] in the first round.<ref>{{cite web|title=European Order of Merit 2014/2015|url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10&season=2014|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> At the non-ranking [[2015 World Grand Prix|World Grand Prix]], Ebdon made a 136 total clearance in the deciding frame of his first round match against [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]] and then defeated [[Stephen Maguire]] 4\u20131.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/sport/other-sport/watch-peter-ebdon-shocks-masters-8861040 | title=Peter Ebdon shocks Masters winner Shaun Murphy at Snooker World Grand Prix | newspaper=[[North Wales Daily Post]] | accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> In the quarter-finals Ebdon was ousted 2\u20134 by [[Martin Gould]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailypost.co.uk/sport/other-sport/watch-stuart-bingham-martin-gould-8887692 | title=Stuart Bingham and Martin Gould book their place in World Grand Prix semis | newspaper=[[North Wales Daily Post]] | accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> He missed out on playing in the [[2015 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] for the second year in a row as [[Stuart Carrington]] beat him 10\u20137 in the second qualifying round.<ref name=\"2014/15\"/>\n\n===2015/2016===\nAt the [[2015 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]], Ebdon beat [[Lu Chenwei]] 6\u20130, [[Dominic Dale]] 6\u20135 and reigning world champion [[Stuart Bingham]] 6\u20133 to reach the fourth round, where he lost 2\u20136 to [[David Grace (snooker player)|David Grace]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/34969568 | title=UK Championship: Peter Ebdon shocks Stuart Bingham | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-3343593/David-Grace-claims-biggest-payday-beating-Peter-Ebdon-reaching-eight-UK-Championship.html | title=David Grace claims biggest payday by beating Peter Ebdon and reaching last eight of UK Championship | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref> At 45, he was the oldest man in the field at the [[2016 World Grand Prix|World Grand Prix]], but knocked out [[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]] 4\u20133, before [[Ding Junhui]] whitewashed him 0\u20134 in the second round.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/ebdon-knocks-out-robertson/ | title=Ebdon Knocks Out Robertson | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref> Ebdon eliminated [[James Wattana]] 10\u20136 in the first round of [[2016 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] qualifying and then incredibly came back from 3\u20139 behind against [[Gerard Greene]] to win 10\u20139 just after 2am.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.skysports.com/more-sports/snooker/news/12243/10239894/peter-ebdon-rallies-to-stun-gerard-greene-in-world-snooker-championship-qualifier | title=Peter Ebdon rallies to stun Gerard Greene in World Snooker Championship qualifier | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] | accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref> He qualified for the first time in three years by defeating [[Ian Burns (snooker player)|Ian Burns]] 10\u20132 and lost 2\u201310 to [[Marco Fu]] in the opening round.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=42&season=2015 | title=Peter Ebdon 2015/2016 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=16 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.localberkshire.co.uk/sport/14432438.Peter_Ebdon_ousted_by_Marco_Fu_and_champion_Stuart_Bingham_on_brink_at_Crucible/ | title=Defending champion Stuart Bingham crashes out of World Championship | publisher=Local Berkshire | accessdate=27 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016/2017===\nEbdon had 4\u20131 victories over [[Zhou Yuelong]], [[Duane Jones (snooker player)|Duane Jones]], and [[Dominic Dale]], to advance to the quarter-finals of the [[2016 Indian Open|Indian Open]] in which he lost 3\u20134 to [[Nigel Bond]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/wilson-to-face-bond-in-semis/ |title=Murphy/McGill/Wilson/Bond Into Semis |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref> He made his 24th appearance at the [[2017 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] after beating [[Michael Holt (snooker player)|Michael Holt]] 10\u20139 on the final black to qualify.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/more-sports/snooker/news/12243/10834963/peter-ebdon-beats-michael-holt-in-epic-world-championship-qualifier|title=Peter Ebdon beats Michael Holt in epic World Championship qualifier|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|accessdate=14 April 2017}}</ref> He recovered from a position of requiring four snookers, to win the 9th frame of his first round match against [[Stuart Bingham]] on a re-spotted black, and only trailed 4\u20135 overnight; however, he was ultimately defeated 5\u201310.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/39619893|title=World Championship 2017: Stuart Bingham beats Peter Ebdon in first round|work=[[BBC Sport]]|accessdate=16 April 2017}}</ref> Ebdon ended the season outside the top 32 in the world rankings for the first time since 1992, as he was ranked 40th.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/rnk/history.asp | title=Ranking History | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Peter Ebdon PHC 2018-6.jpg|thumb|2018 Paul Hunter Classic]]\n<!-- What happened to Ebdon's 2017/2018 season? -->\n\n===2018/2019===\nEbdon appeared in a ranking final for the 18th time in his career at the [[2018 Paul Hunter Classic]]. He faced [[Kyren Wilson]] for the title, but lost out 2\u20134.\n\n==Status==\nEbdon was only the second player to have made two competitive maximum 147 breaks in professional tournament play \u2013 these coming at the Strachan Professional and UK Championship, both in 1992. In the same year, he became the first player to make four centuries in five frames.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/plr/bio/pebdon.shtml|title=snooker.org: Peter Ebdon|website=www.snooker.org}}</ref>\n\nEbdon is renowned for his strict fitness regime to condition himself for snooker, such as swimming one mile every day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.buzzle.com/editorials/4-13-2003-39028.asp|title=WebCite query result|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.today/20120520192409/http://www.buzzle.com/editorials/4-13-2003-39028.asp|archive-date=5 November 2013|access-date=}}</ref> In 2012 he adopted a high-carbohydrate, vegan diet, partly to improve sporting performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.30bananasaday.com/profiles/blogs/new-vegan-lifestyle|title=New Vegan Lifestyle|first1=2012 at 4:38am|last1=Posted by Peter David Ebdon on 6 February|first2=View|last2=Blog|website=www.30bananasaday.com}}</ref> In his first year of following the diet he lost two and a half stone and for September aimed to eat only raw food.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2905127,00.html | title=Raw Deal | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=11 September 2012}}</ref> He is a devotee of [[Napoleon Hill]]'s motivational book ''[[Think and Grow Rich]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/snooker-positive-thinking-takes-ebdon-to-the-summit-124106.html|title=Snooker: Positive thinking takes Ebdon to the summit|date=11 January 2003|first=Brian|last=Viner|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=2 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nEbdon has been criticised in the past by other players on the professional circuit,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2001/dec/14/snooker.scottmurray|title=O'Sullivan passes verdict on 'psycho' Ebdon|date=14 December 2001|first=Scott|last=Murray|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=2 April 2019}}</ref> for his exuberant outpourings of emotion after winning important frames or matches. However, since one particular outburst after potting the match ball against [[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]] during their 2001 World Championship second round encounter \u2013 repeatedly punching the air and shouting \"Come on!\" at the top of his voice \u2013 he has toned down his celebrations significantly.{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n\nEbdon is also [[colour blind]]. In a frame in which the brown ball is in close proximity to a red, he usually asks the referee for help on which ball is which. During a match against [[Simon Bedford]] in the 2008 [[Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]], Ebdon inadvertently potted the brown believing it to be a red.<ref>{{cite\n web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/snooker/7668421.stm|title=Rueful Ebdon mistakes brown for red|date=13 October 2008|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> He made the same mistake in the final of the [[2012 Australian Goldfields Open]] and again in the [[2015 Indian Open]].<ref name=\"aus final\"/>\n\nDuring the [[2012 Australian Goldfields Open]] world number two [[Judd Trump]] labelled Ebdon's playing style as \"a joke\" after his second round 5\u20134 win over [[Ding Junhui]] took almost 5 hours to be completed. The average time between shots was over 30 seconds and the average frame time was 32 minutes.<ref name=\"aus controversy\"/>\n\nDespite Ebdon's playing style, age, appearance and personality he is a popular figure amongst snooker fans. Between frames Ebdon fans are often heard chanting the lyrics \"Eb-don, Eb-don, you're my Eb-don and baby you can ebb me on!\" to the tune of the hit [[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]] song \"[[Sex Bomb]]\".\n\n==Personal life==\nEbdon was born in [[Islington]], before moving to [[Wellingborough]], Northamptonshire. He started his career while at [[Highbury Grove School]], resulting in him not taking his [[O levels]] \u2013 a decision he now regrets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.global-snooker.com/Peter-Ebdon.asp|title=Peter Ebdon|publisher=Global-Snooker.com|accessdate=29 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100806154651/http://www.global-snooker.com/Peter-Ebdon.asp|archivedate=6 August 2010}}</ref>\nIn 2005, he emigrated with his wife Deborah and four children: Ruby Mae, Ethan, Tristan and Clarissa, to [[Dubai]] and lived there until 2009.<ref name=\"Ebdon_Argus\"/> On 22 January 2009 it was revealed that Ebdon had split with his wife by mutual consent.<ref name=\"Snooker Scene Blog\">{{Cite web|url=http://snookerscene.blogspot.com/2009/01/peter-ebdon-statement.html|title=Peter Ebdon statement|publisher=Snooker Scene Blog|accessdate=7 February 2008}}</ref> In 2010 he remarried to Nora, who is [[Hungarians|Hungarian]],<ref name=\"Ebdon_Argus\">{{cite news |last=Marshall |first=Bill |title=Fate plays a large hand for happy Ebdon |date=27 October 2010 |work=[[Telegraph & Argus]] |url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/sportother/8479174.Fate_plays_a_large_hand_for_happy_Ebdon/ |accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref> and has since become a [[vegan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=O'Sullivan Comes Good To Deny Campbell |date=28 March 2010 |work=World Snooker |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2698889,00.html |accessdate=30 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401235401/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~2698889%2C00.html |archivedate=1 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Ebdon recorded a version of the [[David Cassidy]] song \"I Am a Clown\", and it was released as a single.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.last.fm/music/Peter+Ebdon |title=Peter Ebdon |publisher=[[Last.fm]] |accessdate=16 November 2009}}</ref> He has also released a second single, \"Fall of Paradise\", with a video filmed at Burnley's Afterlife Club.{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n\n== Performance and rankings timeline ==\n<div style=\"width:auto; overflow:scroll\">\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0 1em 0 0; border:1px #aaa solid; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:85%\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! '''Tournament'''\n! [[Snooker season 1991/1992|1991/<br/>92]]\n! [[Snooker season 1992/1993|1992/<br/>93]]\n! [[Snooker season 1993/1994|1993/<br/>94]]\n! [[Snooker season 1994/1995|1994/<br/>95]]\n! [[Snooker season 1995/1996|1995/<br/>96]]\n! [[Snooker season 1996/1997|1996/<br/>97]]\n! [[Snooker season 1997/1998|1997/<br/>98]]\n! [[Snooker season 1998/1999|1998/<br/>99]]\n! [[Snooker season 1999/2000|1999/<br/>00]]\n! [[Snooker season 2000/2001|2000/<br/>01]]\n! [[Snooker season 2001/2002|2001/<br/>02]]\n! [[Snooker season 2002/2003|2002/<br/>03]]\n! [[Snooker season 2003/2004|2003/<br/>04]]\n! [[Snooker season 2004/2005|2004/<br/>05]]\n! [[Snooker season 2005/2006|2005/<br/>06]]\n! [[Snooker se